The project focuses on providing an Integrated Water Resource Management (IWRM) solution to hydrological, ecological and water quality challenges in Lac Nokou in Benin.The project consists of ecological recovery through deepening of parts of the lake via dredging, use of dredged sediment for construction of flood defence structures and land reclamation for urban infrastructure development.

To provide multi annual funding to the Stichting Flying Swans, who aims to develop agro logistical cool corridors in emerging markets. The funding will be used to identify and develop projects to become bankable projects in a number of identified countries. In the first scoping phase, Ethiopia and South Africa have been selected.

Wegdam Food Link BV and its local partner in Ghana have jointly set up a successful meat trade in Ghana. With a loan and a guarantee of the DGGF and a loan from Rabobank, Wegdam Food Link BV shall be able to build a cold store in the port of Tema, Ghana. Through this additional cooling capacity, the trade capacity of the Dutch company and its local partner is significantly increased. 50 jobs will be created at the cold store. Furthermore, solar panels will be placed on the roof of the cold store. They will supply a large part of the required energy to the cold store.

Coastal protection infrastructure based on nature-based solutions complemented by flood protection infrastructure, an evacuation and response system and a technical assistance package

AFRIpads was established with a clear goal: to overcome key challenges that women and girls in Africa face whilst on their period in relation to access, affordability and sustainability of quality menstrual products.
With TA support AFRIpads wants to increase the accessibility to affordable, quality menstrual products for women and girls in Africa. This combined with the companys desire to further boost local production, employment and skilling on the one hand, and to extend their business from selling only reusable pads to NGOs to selling reusable and disposable pads to both NGOs and on the consumer market, on the other hand.

A Dutch SME and its local partner want to invest in a cinchona project in Madagascar. This investment is co-financed by DGGF and a Dutch Bank. With regard to a current subsidy programme 26 jobs will be created (now 23). With this expansion project another 33 additional jobs will be added.
